If Dante were alive today, his tenth circle of Hell would surely be the Gardaí. To understand Ireland’s systemic failures, one must grapple with its colonial past. British rule didn’t just exploit the Irish economy; it institutionalized a culture of dependency and cynicism toward authority. The Catholic Church, once the moral arbiter, compounded this by weaponizing faith as a tool of control. Northern Ireland’s descent into sectarian violence exposed the fragility of governance and the myopia of British policy.

The shadow of the Troubles lingers. Policing in Ireland—North and South—remains haunted by the need to maintain "stability," often at the expense of justice. The Gardaí’s reluctance to confront organized crime reflects this unease. Why chase car thieves when paramilitary groups operate with impunity?
